<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910524-0038</DOCNO><DOCID>910524-0038.</DOCID><HL>   Consolidated NBS   Sues Price Waterhouse   And Greenwood Cook</HL><DATE>05/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   T.CNB</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ACCOUNTING (ACC)DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)</IN><NS>ACCOUNTING AND AUDITING NEWS andamp; ISSUES (ACC)</NS><RE>CANADA (CN)NEW YORK (NY)</RE><LP>   TORONTO -- Consolidated NBS Inc. said it sued twoaccounting firms, Price Waterhouse and Greenwood Cook,seeking 135 million Canadian dollars (US$117.4 million) indamages.   Consolidated NBS said the suit was filed in the GeneralDivision of the Ontario Court of Justice. The company saidthe action relates to the audit of its financial statementsbetween 1985 and 1989. The manufacturer of credit cards andrelated equipment didn't elaborate, and company officialscouldn't be reached for comment.</LP><TEXT>   In 1988, an independent audit of National Business SystemsInc., as Consolidated NBS was then called, discovered&quot;unauthorized transfers&quot; of C$10 million in financial assets.   Following the disclosure, the company's president andchief executive resigned, and Hees International Bancorp, aholding company controlled by Toronto's Bronfman family,stepped in to assist the management in restructuring thedebt-laden company. The restructuring process is still underway, Hees officials have said.</TEXT></DOC>